====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# To move or travel slowly.
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=7 Oct 1865|journal=The Mercury|location=Hobart|page=2|passage=But that is a state of things, which must in time work its own cure. We cannot always go dribbling and '''drivelling''' along, government and people alike being the scoff of all onlookers.}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=29 Oct 1872|journal=The Newcastle Chronicle|location=NSW|page=4|passage=There was a good deal of bustle and life at the inn; but three or four inebriates '''drivelling''' about the premises were 'suffering a recovery,' from the excitement of the previous night's entertainment.}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=30 May1914|journal=The Darling Downs Gazette|location=Qld|page=2|passage=Walter was as silly as most men are when in love. He went '''drivelling''' off in pursuit of her "dear little work-worn hands"[.]}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1938|author=Norman Lindsay|authorlink=Norman Lindsay|title=Age of Consent|publisher=Ure Smith|location=Sydney|year_published=1962|page=122|passage='''Drivelling''' back to the shanty at midday presented him with a distracting gamble over lunch.}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=15 Sept 1939|journal=The Daily Examiner|location=Grafton, NSW|page=5|passage="I am amazed to think we are in the second week of war and this country is still '''drivelling''' along with a small volunteer force," he added.}}
# To use up or to be used up.
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=17 Aug 1858|journal=The Ovens and Murray Advertiser|location=Beechworth, Vic|page=2|passage=Instead of '''drivelling''' away the precious initiative season of life in the vain labour of teaching tuneable voices to sing[.]}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=31 Aug 1872|journal=The Mercury|location=Hobart|page=2|passage=It is for the country to say whether we are to keep on in this backward course, whether we are to go on getting deeper and deeper into debt, whether we are to have increased taxation year after year. The bone and sinew of the land is '''drivelling''' away.}}

